Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been severely hit by financial instability and sudden changes in market dynamics.
Other events of this kind are likely, because, coming out of the crisis, the global economy is imbalanced in many aspects, particularly in terms of sovereign debt and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are the cause of most crises and present a challenge for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect safely and even more difficult to prove.
Then, predicting the exact moment of the tipping point (when the bubbles burst, when the markets are paralyzed, and when credit is no longer available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are strongly non-linear events that occur without warning signs.
Periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those who are least responsible.
If this pattern were to repeat, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could herald excessive regulations, a reassertion of the state, and a withdrawal from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is turning into a sovereign debt crisis for advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can result in a dangerous fiscal imbalance, characterized by declining tax revenues and increased bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" in advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
Undetected imbalances and systemic risks mean that fiscal policies that seem prudent are not actually prudent.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the beginning of the crisis.
But his revenues and expenses were largely determined by a real estate bubble linked to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which tax consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is probably a typical example.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructurings or through inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, it must be that "sovereign" states are attentive to the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk and taking corrective measures quickly.
New detailed legislative frameworks emphasizing capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings and other information sources, incentives, conflicts of interest and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection and resolution mechanisms are about to be adopted.
There is hope that these reforms will reduce the likelihood and severity of systemic risks.
But they will do nothing to resolve the issue of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition to and in complement to new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some politicians and leading analysts consider such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, to be futile.
Incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex, constantly evolving global financial system mean, according to them, that risk detection is either impossible or so prone to error that this effort would be unproductive.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If the skeptics are right, we then have to accept that we will periodically be in a situation of financial and fiscal instability that we cannot predict in advance.
We should then also accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than what we considered necessary just three years ago.
In the fields of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one consists of rejecting a true proposition, and the other is accepting a false proposition.
We will call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be phrased as follows: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the most likely high cost?
Opponents of prudent surveillance of systemic risks hold two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur, because there is no reliable indicator of an increasing potential instability.
Looking for such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantly.
But this position seems deceptive.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took note of them.
One must however admit that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the tipping point.
They were undeniably signs.
The second position is that there are indeed foreshadowing signs, but they are so unreliable that taking action would do more harm than good.
This viewpoint implies that AQF has a likely higher cost than RQV, because there are many false positives and/or the remedy is worse than the illness.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so that the aggregate negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I, for my part, am not convinced.
There may be a deeper trend toward openness.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty and errors are frequent.
The default position of decision-makers in advanced countries seems to be that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply rooted belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulating.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refrain from acting unless one has good reasons to do so.
But given past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at the very least questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to design and that the cost of AQF errors is higher than the cost of RQV errors.
But we should at least attempt the experiment, and assign for this purpose responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing institution, which has access to relevant information, possesses analytical skills at both the financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively free from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and thus influence the perception of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the financial system's capacity to self-regulate.
